entry.title: Revert "media/gpu/test: Fix H.264 NALU boundary detection"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a801c6cd3fd9ef31b78a29ea0f86957077d72a81.



Reason for revert: Broke tast video.ChromeStackDecoder.*h264*



Bug: b:299844840



Original change's description:

> media/gpu/test: Fix H.264 NALU boundary detection

>

> video_decode_accelerator_(perf_)test's EncodedDataHelper is used for

> reading H.264 (and other codecs ofc) bitstreams frames from disk. To

> find the NALU boundary, it looks for the marker 0x00 00 00 01; however,

> NALUs can also be marked by 0x00 00 01 (*); this CL fixes this.

>

> This situation was found during V4L2StatefulVideoDecoder bringup: it

> was observed that said decoder was fed very large media::DecoderBuffers

> for some H.264 specific "main" test vectors (e.g. CAPCM1_Sand_E.h264)

> and this was traced down to EncodedDataHelper not reading one NALU at

> a time from disk, but bundling very many at once.

>

> With this CL, all H.264 main test vectors verify MD5Sums on trogdor

> _except_ for CVPCMNL2_SVA_C.h264 (argh! :).

>

> (*) This is described in the spec but a quick search gives as well e.g.

> https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/directshow/h-264-video-types#h264-bitstream-with-start-codes

>

entry.title: Use the standard-compliant forbidden character '^' as an invalid URL
entry.content:
Currently, in the rewriting rule of the test runners, "~NOTFOUND" is

used as an invalid URL. However, '~' is NOT a forbidden character

according to the URL standard.



Chromium is addressing [1] this non-compliant behavior and will permit

'~' character in URL hosts. Thus, we can no longer use "~NOTFOUND" as

it will become a valid URL.



As an alternative, any invalid character is acceptable. Let's use '^'

because '^' is a forbidden character both before and after the CL [1].



The PR for WPT Chrome runner is:

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/41840/



[1]: https://crrev.com/c/4823237

entry.title: [Lacros] Align alt+N accelerator behavior with Ash
entry.content:
In Lacros Only, the alt+N accelerator behavior regresses because it is

now handled by a new class BrowserAppShelfItemController for

Lacros-chrome, Ash-backed SWA and Lacros-backed PWA. In the past it was

AppShortcutShelfItemController for handling Ash-backed SWA and PWA, and

BrowserShortcutShelfItemController for handling Ash-chrome. This CL

borrows the UX from the old classes and reimplements it in

BrowserAppShelfItemController for Lacros Only mode.



To review this CL one may find the following context useful.



* How Alt+N was handled in Ash-chrome era?



Before Lacros Only mode was rolled out, Ash-chrome was the browser and

both SWA and PWA were backed by Ash-chrome. There were two classes

involved in handling Alt+N. They were BrowserShortcutShelfItemController

and AppShortcutShelfItemController. Specifically, the former was for

handling Ash-chrome icon, while the latter was for handling SWA and PWA

icons backed by Ash-chrome.



* How Alt+N is handled in Lacros-chrome era?



When Lacros-chrome arrives, specifically, when Lacros Only is rolled

out, all three cases (the browser, SWA, PWA) are all handled by the same

class BrowserAppShelfItemController.



* Why I can trigger the accelerator just by pressing without releasing?



Even though the code in all three aforementioned classes says it is

handling the ui::ET_KEY_RELEASED typed ui::KeyEvent. The event is in

fact manufactured by the caller right before it is passed in. One such

example of the caller is [1]. In all three cases, It takes a key press

to trigger the call, rather than a key release.



[1]:https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/tags/117.0.5901.1:ash/shelf/shelf.cc;l=402

mandatory re-auth opt-in flow to offer opt-in in the case where a user

goes through non-interactive authentication, but then manually fills a

different card.



This CL specifically focuses on creating a new histogram and updating

the enums for the checkout opt-in decision metrics logging. It also

creates a new enum for the mandatory re-auth opt-in update source

metrics logging.
